thank you @andrewlewis for the hint. it is working as you suggest:
```
@Override
public long open(DataSpec dataSpec) throws HttpDataSourceException
{
	final Map<String, String> m1 = dataSpec.httpRequestHeaders;
	final Map<String, String> m2 = new HashMap<>();
	for (Map.Entry<String, String> entry : m1.entrySet())
		if(!entry.getKey().equals(IcyHeaders.REQUEST_HEADER_ENABLE_METADATA_NAME))
			m2.put(entry.getKey(), entry.getValue());
	
	return super.open(dataSpec.withRequestHeaders(m2));
}
```
And thankfully the web server behavior is correct now. I'm not facing the same issues that i faced in #7353 which indicates that setting ICY_Metadata in the header by default is not the correct way. Many web servers might be affected by this (at least in my case which i have it on bluehost, one of the leaders in this market).

I think we should have an easy way to configure the dataspec.httpRequestHeaders

thank you again

