Not sure if you aware, but you get events for all these user interactions by adding an `EventListener` to the `Player`. This should already cover most of the required events:
```
player.addEventListener(new Player.EventListener() {
  boolean previousPlayWhenReady = false;
  int previousWindowIndex = 0;

  @Override
  public void onPlayerStateChanged(boolean playWhenReady, int state) {
    if (previousPlayWhenReady == false && playWhenReady == true) {  
      // Play clicked.
    }
    else if (previousPlayWhenReady == true && playWhenReady == false) {
      // Pause clicked.
    }
    previousPlayWhenReady = playWhenReady;
  }
 
  @Override
  public void onPositionDiscontinuity(@Player.DiscontinuityReason int reason) {
    if (reason == DISCONTINUITY_REASON_SEEK
        && previousWindowIndex + 1 == player.getCurrentWindowIndex()) {
      // Next clicked.
    }
    if (reason == DISCONTINUITY_REASON_SEEK
        && previousWindowIndex - 1 == player.getCurrentWindowIndex()) {
      // Previous clicked.
    }
    previousWindowIndex = player.getCurrrentWindowIndex();
  }

  @Override
  public void onTimelineChanged(Timeline timeline, int reason) {
    previousWindowIndex = player.getCurrrentWindowIndex();
  }
});
```

The only potential problem is that the same events are triggered if you call `player.setPlayWhenReady(...)`, `player.next()` or `player.previous()` in code without UI interaction.

